The two men who may influence whether blood will flow again on Egypt's streets both spent last week abroad. One of the two glided back to Cairo's airport on Friday. The country's president Abdel Fattah el-Sisi returned from the UN general assembly. The ex-general, who in 2013 removed Muslim brother Mohammed Mursi, the country's first freely elected head of state, from power had spent a pleasant time in New York. US president Donald Trump had praised Sisi's approach towards political Islam and not lost a word over human rights violations at the Nile. This was during a week in which Egypt's security forces had arrested hundreds of people because they had dared to protest against the president. Sisi said in front of state TV's microphones at the airport that he had "no cause for concern." The Egyptians "won't let themselves be led astray."
