When Internet Providers Promise Too Much
If your Internet connection seems to be slower than your internet provider advertised, there are several ways you can look into this.
When you sign an internet service agreement, you do not have to blindly trust your provider’s performance claims. As a customer, if you feel there is an irregularity, you can check the speed yourself.
After all, the promised data transfer rates are part of your agreement and should therefore be achieved, says the Consumers' Center in Bavaria.
If your connection always seems to be much slower than the provider advertised, there are several ways to test this. For instance, the measurement tools of the Federal Network Agency (BNetzA) measure the actual data transfer rates and compare them with the rate agreed upon in the contract.
“The tests of the providers, however, follow provider-specific standards and are therefore not uniformly and objectively calculated,” the Consumers' Center in Bavaria points out on its website.
If the connection is significantly slower than advertised, customers can set the provider a reasonable deadline - usually 14 days - to provide the promised service. This is best done by registered mail.
If that has no effect, even after repeated requests, customers can cancel their contract and possibly even claim damages. In the absence of success, however, the only remaining option is legal action.
First Senior Republican in Favor of Investigation
